The Prague Stock Exchange is at a disadvantage at the end of the trade
The Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses after the morning crash.
Transactions with shares in the Czech Energy Industry Company (<0xC4><0x8C>EZ) reached nearly half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued its Monday fall from the beginning of Tuesday’s trading, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the fall in Wall Street shares is behind the decline.
This is how the market reacts to the outcome of the vote in the US House of Representatives, which has refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Shares in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in stocks on Tuesday, although some of the losses were eventually eliminated during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market index accounted for almost four percent of the trade, but later it cancelled some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks, fell 3.8 percent in the Hong Kong stock exchange and closed markets in Shanghai.
The stock on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwanese stock market fell by 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
“The timing of the US rescue operation is uncertain and affects the world’s financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although a part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the central bank of China.
In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should resume negotiations immediately and accept the financial system’s support proposal.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will also be aware of the consequences.
The Blood Bath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which would have cost $700 billion (almost $12 trillion).
The lawmakers thus ignored President Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath, and leading stock indices recorded the largest fall in 20 years.
Dow Jones fell by almost seven percent, the last time it experienced a similar fall was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal had not been accepted in the House of Representatives, the index started to fall free.
Congress withdraws: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
The U.S. Congress chiefs and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement and financial assistance for the U.S. financial system.
They will vote on this at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in the negotiations on the approval of the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about $12 trillion).
But there is no victory yet.
Congress must complete some of the details of the agreement before it can make public the final form of the law and their votes.
The draft financial support for the system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, he informed Reuters news agency Barney Frank, Chairman of the Financial Organizations Committee.
According to Senate sources, the draft is likely to be voted on as soon as Wednesday.
Economists say there should be a announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, there will be a "forethought" afterwards.
Paulson: The plan should be effective
“We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our different views on what the form of a package for stabilising the market should be,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat at Bloomberg.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislature met with Henry Paulson, the U.S. Treasury Secretary, on Saturday night to form a permanent government fund.
This should buy from financial companies the unsold mortgages that put financial firms in grave losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a final agreement on a draft that will work, and that should be effective on the market at the same time.
The repair proposal still needs to be continued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Sign for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling violently.
Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada said the lawmakers were trying to reach an agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian money markets, where the time zone could be the first to influence Monday’s trading.
It is not yet clear, however, when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, as well as whether the trial can be stopped at the last minute due to a problem.
The legislators hope that the law will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law still undergoes a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
According to President Bush, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
However, Congress could block the issue of the remaining amount, which was set at an additional $100 billion and later at $350 billion if it feels that the program is not performing its function.
Bush Appreciates Progress in Negotiations
Although the President may veto this decision, the Congress may override its veto.
However, despite these changes, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire the financial means to purchase bad mortgage securities that lost their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgage loans.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
With the progress made in the negotiations, President Bush was also pleased.
Tony Fratto, a spokesman for Bush, said the president was “satisfied with Saturday’s progress and appreciated the two-party effort to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of Busy End Satisfactions
Christopher Dodd, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said the lawmakers had agreed on the responsibility for the financial program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the closure of benefits, and the timing of the financing plan.
The new law also limits the so-called "busy suffocations" of the directors participating in the program and establishes a fund monitoring committee.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this, and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and will be useful to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance to homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should create new installments for the mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly installments of the debtors and enabling them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual Aid
According to David Marek, senior economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“This is because we don’t know what mechanism and at what price the problematic actives will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will divide the losses,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it is not so important that the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“It is more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give their blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment,” Marek said.
Parallel blade: MP3 players versus mobiles.
We help you choose
While almost all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be reached.
It seems that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-end expensive record player at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl discs, you probably dream of such a disc player.
This is similar to the one intended for travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue 8,000 crowns for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan is likely to find it difficult to accept a twenty-coron market earphone.
Two extremes, between which everyone has enough space.
There is a wide selection.
The life of the batteries also counts
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just playing music, but also something that most mobiles don’t even accidentally do.
No device today is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, you can also play music and video, record both, have a better-badger camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a little miracle, as no refrigerator can grill and no television can take photos.
However, multi-function mobiles also have drawbacks.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more time the display sends to the charger.
And music playing is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobiles, count on them not to play for you for more than a few hours.
Even if you’re on the phone here and there, get a charger for your workplace – this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have such a problem, even worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope with miniature memory cards used in mobile devices without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod), players do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
The majority of mobiles and players already create their own music library based on the artist, album, genre name, or user’s evaluation.
Some devices only represent a tree structure like Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to handle, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, you should primarily ask about battery life, memory capacity, sound output quality and type, and, of course, the convenience of the treatment.
If the music is primarily a background for you and you only listen to it for a short time every day, for example, on the tram, any mobile device that plays MP3 will suit you.
Any mobile phone can do that.
You don’t have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player knows.
With MP3, each of them will cope, and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most popular, and the vast majority of the devices also cope with WMA format music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and your iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also allow online music shopping, for example.
It is enough to visit the respective pages of the provider (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a powerful argument for the mobile acquisition of music.
Unfortunately, the supply of service providers is crappy and is usually limited to one-year-old radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this type of selling of music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, your mobile is tapped out in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is lying at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry the headphones or at least the hands-free ones.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which has almost all mobile, but few MP3 players.
For many, music mobiles will probably have the biggest benefit of the price.
The cheapest ones are usually less than three thousand crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a fair enough walkman.
However, you are mostly limited by the lack of conventional earphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns with traditional 3.5 mm diameter hole earphones.
However, the advantages of players are, among other things, simple handling.
With the simplest - certainly not necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection), everyone really copes.
Minimal function, handling similar to the usual cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of a crash in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile internet, nor is there any risk of data transmission for the subsequent huge account.
Which device to choose
The cheapest mobile devices (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an opening for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
When you buy the right card, it can cost up to two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The base types only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or irate.
Based on the capacity (up to 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroons.
If you belong to more demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the convenience of the treatment approaches the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson is the farthest in the industry, which has the same user interface for walkman series mobiles as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players from the above brands can offer the same service in the same price range up to 4 000 kroons, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
However, something is missing for us here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be that long.
On Mobil.cz we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
After the last step of the European Commission, roaming charges may be regulated in a contradictory situation - some customers of Czech mobile operators will be cheaper than their own.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and have a penetration that is higher than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has often agreed to this, who has previously stated several times that there is no room for new service providers in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classical service provider with its own network is unlikely to have too many chances (although it would be difficult to find a frequency).
However, there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, which the classic service providers also had to react to.
Even before big fish such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile were introduced to the market in Great Britain, sounds similar to ours were heard.
However, it has been proven that such service providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, we do not have to go too far for example.
In February this year, we informed you about the departure of the Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the Penta Financial Group, which also owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much smaller target group.
For efficient operation, you need far fewer customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world usually appear as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and sms, but they often offset it with fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages that are at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider is specifically focused on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, a virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar idea to that of Poland can work for us.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesperson for Vodafone, doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
It is also relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem too hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
This indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition can be created.
The GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in starting a virtual service provider for some time now, which aims to take another step to make Telefonica O2 a true competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers not only wired but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have discussed this opportunity again with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
There may be better times.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual service provider can be lucky by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
“At this moment, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider would have a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
Until now, we have not been invited by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area,” he mentioned to Mobil.cz from the Press Department of Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica 02.
Other suppliers also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesman for T-Mobile, said: "Unfortunately, we have not yet recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects on which to build."
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network, by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will appear.
There should be a concrete agreement on our table right now so that we can think in such a short term.”
Vodafone prefers to focus its attention on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, primarily in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most rewarding for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is partnering to build networks shared with high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - a string with service providers
The process of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another provider would mean increased competition, lower prices and thus lower profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When service providers have something important, they are able to work together, as evidenced by the history of the birth of the U:fon.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably around the birth of the U:fon of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument as to why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: “The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been influenced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be highly demanding."
In view of this attitude of mobile operators, however, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory bodies is quite amazing.
In the meantime, it is not only the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C><0xC3><0x9A>, which in the Czech Republic, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition.
Only the Hungarian Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a characteristic relation to the whole problem.
“The entry of a virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the supply of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers,” said Kristián Chlapua, the foreign relations department of the Hungarian Competition Authority.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, make sure that no one can re-establish their market position, this is more than strange.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: “In a foreign country where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the price of mobile phone services.”
However, it is likely that the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS are not subject to pressure to ensure the proper functioning of the market environment and to reduce prices.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the reaction of the three mobile operators is quite touching.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Just like at filling stations, the same gas prices are probably just a result of coincidence and hard competition.
"In this case, the Office did not discover the signs of anti-competitive proceedings, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither service provider has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately greater responsibility for its market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are also likely to be missing to the telecom regulator,” Chalupa said.
The presentation of market leadership is one of the many points of debate.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position in such a market.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So, in a certain segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if this argument were not accepted, it should be a minimum warning for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are acting in a strikingly similar way.
Meanwhile, complaints from interested parties (including the already mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all service providers.
And to shift responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hand off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications could not be carried through, although many experts hoped for an improvement in the situation.
This should be well known to the representatives of the UOHS, but their interests are likely to be different.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of fake virtual service providers, many of which already operate in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies that have their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
These are multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts against the service provider as a classic corporate client, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a prominent customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar advances.
"If there were cases of breach of contract terms that you are talking about, it could be a breach of contract terms that we would be dealing with and that could lead to the termination of our cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová said in a statement.
But it is quite unlikely that news of such activity would not have reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, there are thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider is defending itself against such a procedure.
These companies do not have negligible profits and, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not particularly threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not on their name, so they cannot have it in its entirety as the general customers of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0xBA> should be.
In addition, another question arises for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they obstructing the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong right to expose such an activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they have not suspected such a thing and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the prices of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classic service providers tried to prevent them more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small or perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory bodies intervened at this very moment, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they reached the conclusion that the first virtual service provider was created, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are giving the whole case to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that inconclusive competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If a service provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, <0xC3><0x9A>OHS can only be difficult to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be able to make more expensive calls.
