Rats have emotions too.
A rat or a moth escapes in case of danger. Does that mean you feel fear?
Joseph LeDoux, a neurologist, is convinced that animals have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
For years, scientists have been publishing their articles in the Internet magazine "Edge".
SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of every human brain is the same.
However, as we look at other species and examine the issues of perception or, in general, consciousness, we arrive in difficult terrain, because the hardware is not the same.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: pretending to be dead, fleeing or attacking.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers deduce comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe in that.
The two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to the animals.
On the one hand, human-conscious circuits almost always contain the side prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and implementation/control functions).
This wide area is higher in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other beings.
At least in the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are, or in the case of planning and decision-making ability, it can be reasonably assumed that man is different from even other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that it depends on consciousness.
In this case, the animals can be excluded.
However, even if the language were not dependent on the mind, the language would certainly be influenced, so that the animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness can be like for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and due to the special hardware it cannot be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research will bring us serious problems.
Most of my reflections relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on short-term memory of primates, especially in the case of visualization.
However, this assumption, examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What follows from this in terms of emotions?
This is due to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call “fear” is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity (or its consequences, for example, bodily reactions) of a localized defense system in the brain occupies a working memory.
In this way, emotions are closely related to those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially of humans.
In addition to language, perception is divided into subtle stages, because with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorise states in order to describe them to others as well as ourselves.
