Falling drunk drivers will be forced to install "Alcolock"
After three drunk driving offences, the Ministry of the Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the structure.
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, which states that the pilot project will last for a year.
As the aim of the project is to re-enter the market, the driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on traffic education.
In addition to the General Public Prosecutor’s Office for Transport Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the FITSA Foundation for Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA) also participate in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers arrested several times because of drunk driving are back in the car.
Alcolock would prevent this, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the inflated air. If it is larger than allowed, or if the driver did not inflate at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of an instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the infringer.
A study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of violations by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, this rule is estimated to save 115 lives a year.
The measure focuses on offences for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming criminal offences,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, as the implementation of the legal reform is carried out in the usual way, while the necessary criminal reform would require amendment of the Fundamental Law.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although in experimental mode it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
The House will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party which, on the basis of the French model, calls for the system to be installed in school buses.
