Those who speak in their sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I’m not talking about those who get upset and tell them what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that you spoke at night.
In terms of frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a disease with high fever), or more regular (daily, weekly or monthly) and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
Often combined with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night-time wake-up, night-time bed wear (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As already mentioned, a condition with high fever may be accompanied by stress or heightened excitement.
In any case, little has been studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, it can consist of incoherent words or grumbling, but in contrast, it can also occur in the form of shouting, crying, or prolonged speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination may reveal whether there is any problem causing great anxiety in the background and thus offer a solution.
As we have already mentioned, this is a benign phenomenon, and consequently there is no cure for it unless it is accompanied by some other form of sleep disorder that can be treated (such as insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things we can do, here is a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure the child stays calm before going to bed.
Choose soothing games and avoid watching scary or more aggressive TV shows or series.
For children prone to nervousness or more difficult to relax, we teach some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This helps the child to sleep more peacefully.
If you still start talking while you sleep, try to keep your calm.
Remember, this is harmless to the child, and the next day they won't remember anything.
Useful advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be superfluous, because the child is unconscious, but it would shrink from sleep.
Despite speaking, he actually continues to sleep and rest.
Keep in mind, if you have multiple episodes of severe anxiety accompanied by this phenomenon, it is advisable to consult a specialist or explore what causes the child to become very anxious.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), don’t start asking him to find out anything.
It would be unnecessary, because you are not so conscious when you sleep that you are not conscious enough to gather your thoughts.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but you cannot see the dream images associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and the possible conclusions.
Never tell a child that they can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, as this is just a few minutes of harmless episode.
