The blood is safe again.
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary of its foundation. President Dr. Francine Décary had a good reason to celebrate because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world today.
And most importantly, he managed to regain the trust of people, which was severely shaken by the blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the Canadian Red Cross Blood Supply Service treated nationwide blood reserves infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and general upheaval, the Canadian government launched a formal investigation in February 1994 led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to formulate proposals to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever was delayed in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own commission to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood-supply services were established in Canada: the Héma Québec, which serves Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Supply Company, which is responsible for the supply of blood to all the other provinces and the two territories.
“When Héma-Québec began its activity in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system,” said Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
“In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we have managed to regain the trust of people,” Décary says proudly, according to the report, as early as 2008, nearly 94% of the population in Quebec believed that Héma-Québece was reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that “trust is a very fragile thing.”
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, a number of cases have been discovered in Europe where people have also been infected with a new variant of the disease Creutzfeldt-Jakob, a doctor who has been in charge of the company since its foundation in 1998.
“We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are insecure and at risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusion measures. In this case, it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes a change in the brain, thus inevitably leading to death.
Therefore, in April 1999 we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was decided beyond any doubt that the disease spreads through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies against the virus, on which previous tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to a period of less than one week.
Thus, the risk of blood donors infecting blood without knowing it and of not being able to detect it was significantly mitigated.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS spreading through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to 1.
“In other words, we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 and 500 thousand blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that now anyone can safely accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health, says Héma-Québec’s number one leader.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what kind of new pathogen will be introduced into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with an insect bite.
Therefore, we must be constantly on guard," said Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, demand is also increasing.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also affects the population of blood donors, as the number of people able to donate blood in the network is only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, any healthy person, at least 18 years of age, who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because, for example, they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is devastating are not eligible for a year to donate blood.
“We have 3 percent of our reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare that we run out of stocks.
However, the number of blood donors must be increased to the extent that existing ones age, because after a while they can no longer give blood.
But it is very difficult to convince people to give blood, but it is even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today’s busy world, one hour of man’s time is scarce enough to go and give blood,” says Francine Décary.
The Héma Québec, which operates from a $297 million annual budget, not only provides blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeball tissues and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned individuals.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages Quebec’s only public stem cell bank.
Once treated only as medical waste, umbilical cords can produce blood that is rich in stem cells, allowing for the treatment of serious diseases (such as leukemia).
“We celebrated a few weeks ago that we had the thousandth umbilical cord blood sample in our bank, and we are planning to take out more than a thousand new samples a year.
“At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering these for organ transplants,” said Dr. Décary, who believes that the umbilical cord blood extraction program is very popular today.
“Many mothers are saddened by the fact that they don’t have the opportunity to do so” – indeed, this is because Héma-Québec has no way of making this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
