Opinion - Barrick Gold orwelli's Vocabulary
In Le Devoir's September 17 issue, a letter was published by Patrick J. Garver, vice president and chief executive of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada.
As a result of Orwelli’s discussion, Garver states that the world’s largest gold-producing company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small-money publishing company to initiate a so-called “public debate.”
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decision, especially in defamation lawsuits, is not based on the truth, but on the law.
It is not surprising that Garver listened deeply to this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate to destroy anyone whose position is contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend significant amounts of money on defense and combat in an unequal fight where on the other hand there is an army of lawyers supported by almost inexhaustible sources in the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, however, the tactics of destroying the defendant and making a friendly agreement are often used, not only to silence the opposite, but even to intimidate those who would try to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he would have had to explain his views to the public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold is active, this is done differently, in Canada, the parties to the dispute usually do not hit each other with a stick, but tell their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have had enough to open its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media and publications, paying independent research teams to shed light on the issue.
But it seems Barrick Gold doesn't trust the public, and with one move, he's sweeping away requests and letters written to protect Noir Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can initiate a 'public' debate if, at the same time, he disregards the opinion of this public?
In the head of the vice-president, this word probably means only the lawyers who have been paid for the busily, rather than the whole population of Canada: the meaning of the concept is narrowed down.
In a democratic state, even those who abuse others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand – or does not want to understand – that Noir Canada’s authors and publishers are primarily supported by the public because it condemns the harsh method of mining.
The public is willing to listen to Barrick and make a judgment, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments, rather than by a case of silence for many. (In connection with the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently called in writing the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using this term.)
In addition to Garver’s surreal reflections, Barrick Gold’s procedure is an open attack on the freedom of university research and the search for truth, which are the building blocks of all democratic societies.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources, to debate facts and their interpretation, which form the basis of spiritual activities.
If, in a country like Canada, you can only study and discuss topics that do not please the rich companies of today’s world, who will take the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it could do so in accordance with the scientific standards applied by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have the right to reply.
In our university community, we have been able to deal with disputes, differences and conflicts for a long time.
Barrick Gold's unthinkable procedure shows that, contrary to his claim, he had no desire to argue.
This is a loss both for the world of universities and for the Canadian public debate institution. It is time for governments to implement measures that limit legal proceedings for such abuse.
Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans Agree
Yesterday, the Republican and Democratic leaders of the Bush administration and Congress finally reached an agreement on the economic rescue operation, which has been the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months is yet to be approved by the two Houses of Congress.
The essential elements of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by the representatives; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the envisaged public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses reserved for failure to pay; right of access to the remuneration of managers of the companies benefiting from assistance.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Nancy Pelosi, president of the U.S. House of Representatives, and Judd Gregg, the Republican MP at the trial, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial was over.
“We have made a big step forward towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a spokesman for the Bush administration.
“We have done everything we can to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“The most important aspect is that if we don’t do this, there will be a huge shock, chaos, and confusion in the daily lives of Americans,” Republican MEP Judd Gregg said.
The trial was accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on the mood of investors.
The deal was granted a deadline until the stock exchange opened this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed a willingness to reach an agreement, however, they expressed that they were not happy that the situation had intensified to the very end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with extending the agreement to include elements such as provisions on the preservation of house ownership or the payment of government-assisted directors.
“When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps because of the irresponsibility of other people, it is not very welcome.
“These steps are necessary,” he said on a television show in the United States.
When his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied, "I would like to know the details, but I hope so."
“What I have read in large lines can be seen from the fact that it is something that we all have to digest and through which we can move on.
The possibility of not doing anything is simply unacceptable,” he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would buy the dubious claims of U.S. financial institutions, some of their unsold, risky assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the collapse of the real estate mortgage. This first resulted in the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgages), then spread to other debt securities (trade) and finally caused the freezing of liquid assets and the expansion of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft deal was dropped by a group of Republicans last week.
It seems that we have managed to get out of this deadlock since the Democrats agreed to secure some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, rather than buy them.
In order to ensure that all members of Congress are satisfied, a provision has been included in the plan, which stipulates that if the government has to bear losses for five years under the programme, it may impose new taxes to recover its funds.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion tranche would be paid out first, followed by an additional $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress with another vote.
In return for the aid, Washington acquires a stake in the subsidised companies, which will give it a dividend on profits and which it can sell after the crisis has stalled.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of real estate to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan, and may also set the maximum value of the wage and the final severance payable to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters of the plan would like the House to vote on the plan today and the Senate to vote on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
Yesterday, statements against the plan were repeated among both Republicans and Democrats.
"It is quite clear that Washington will not hear your voice," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, said in a statement.
“Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is nothing that would benefit the taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, the Democratic leader of a small congressional group called the “Sceptic faction,” presents things differently, but he comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred outstanding economists, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, have written to us to ask Congress not to rush and carefully examine which path it chooses,” Sherman said.
In Europe, at the same moment, it was once again understood that this was a global crisis.
After a crisis conference, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalize a portion of the Fortis banking group at a value of €11.2 billion (16.3 billion USD).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy its bankruptcy competitor after losing EUR 2 million (US$ 2.9 billion) as a result of the US secondary mortgage crisis.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest European banks and ten largest insurance companies.
"This is not money thrown away," Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“In return, we get the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly something that depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the La Manche, the British government appears to be preparing to nationalise another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over the total amount of ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley bank, of which real estate loans amount to <0xC2><0xA3>41 billion (US$75,5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they would acquire the UK bank’s subsidiaries and customer base.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank to be nationalized by the British government since the start of the crisis.
