The psychology of over-reliance: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
Neuro-economical foundations of this known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been explored by researchers from the University of New York, neurologist and economist.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to miss out on a type of competition like eBay’s auction, so they pay too high a price.
The research attempted to map the nervous system pattern of this "play" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers lotteryd, while the other group of players participated in an auction, while using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) to study the active brain areas of the subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which an important element is the over-bidder of the other side - the complex under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, entered into intense action when the game was lost.
In addition to several other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of striatum.
In support of their theory, the members of the research group, economists, also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against a partner in various circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product concerned and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they came out of the game winning, they would receive a commission of $15 more.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that one of them emphasized the win and the other the loss.
However, proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing against "loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and "winning" groups.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of victory and the avoidance of risk.
Neurological imaging methods alone helped resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now reaching a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is cited as one of the leading causes of death.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis, but only seven thousand are treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a common name for liver infections caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, they are characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused by them differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the feed channel (e.g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D, and other viruses with blood and body fluids (thrush, vaginal discharge, saliva).
In any case, passengers should be vaccinated against A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis Symptoms occur two to three weeks after eating an infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, the jaundice on the skin and on the whites of the eyes develops, the stool is light, the urine becomes dark, the healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die every year from the more severe form of the disease, hepatitis B-induced liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only 1 in 10 infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can also lead to cirrhosis, liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases, only after 20-30 years, the first symptoms appear.
Therefore, it is very important to carry out early prevention, regular screening tests.
In three groups, the incidence of this disease is much higher than the average: between people who had undergone blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and the tattooed.
There are currently 200 million people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus worldwide.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth contacting your GP if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognising the disease can be cured in time, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organised in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of their development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller that could have made it easier for Catholic martyrs to die.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects people’s sense of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked, while all of them studied a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research in which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university are involved.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a sparking device to the left hand of the subject, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked the participants to look closely at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci’s picture of Lady with Hermelin painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a kind of religious state among the faithful, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts, either looking at the religious topic or the general picture.
Catholics reported that during the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe” as if they were “careful” and “quiet, peace filled them.”
While viewing the religious image, 12 percent less pain was reported than when they saw Leonardo’s creation in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the study, believes that similar effects can be achieved by any powerful image, even in atheists, only the right photo should be found.
“We should find a picture that is very positive for them, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
