The flight of the dongo is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions, if not to imitate obstacle sensors in the natural world?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, dongo bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C, a robotic mini-car with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that eliminates all collisions.
During the flight, each bee develops its own oval-shaped personal space, which in fact is very similar to our safety case, said Kazuhiro Doi, Director of PR and R&D Technology at the exhibition.
It is important to play a role in the complex eyes of the uterus, which can see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the complex eye function, the engineers came up with the idea of a laser telemeter.
This identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid collision.
During a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and the autorobot immediately changes direction by rotating its wheels to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the auto-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto-robot project.
It should respond in an intuitive and immediate manner, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety cover, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibility for bees to bypass other bees, only the rotating movement and acceleration as well as the deceleration were used as an option for the autorobot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, an instinctive intelligent reaction is the ability to process, not to process, even less store data.
This structure only needs to process and react to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory at all times.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate bypass technology, which, according to Nissan’s estimate, could enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
An additional application option may be to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system in order to avoid obstacles on the road leading the car to the specified end goal.
