Industrial prices have increased further
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, compared to 12.9 percent in August 2007, reports the KSH.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of the change in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than in the previous year.
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased only marginally by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly by 0.1% compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather product and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8%), mainly due to the 4.6% increase in the price of bags, belts and footwear production and the 2.5% monthly increase in the price of footwear production.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials has resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6%).
There was a price drop in oil processing (1.4%), electrical machinery, instrument manufacturing (0.9%) and - to a minimum - wood processing (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured price growth between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In August, prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which represents a significant weight in the domestic sales of the industry, increased by 0.3 percent, mainly as a result of the protracted impact of the official gas price increase from 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, in terms of domestic sales of manufacturing sectors, prices in the petroleum processing sector increased most (32.4%).
The production of metal processing products in the sector has seen an increase of 13.2 per cent in prices in the food, beverage and tobacco production, which are the most important weight.
Price reductions occurred in the manufacturing of textiles, textile goods (2.5 per cent) and electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent) sectors.
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 percent in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7 per cent higher than one year earlier.
In August, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 %) in the investment goods manufacturing sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, and in the energy and re-use sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy and re-use sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 per cent and a 1.4 per cent decrease in the price of investment goods.
The export sales prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 per cent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro in one month, by 7.1 percent compared to the dollar, by 7.5 percent compared to the euro in August 2007, and by 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
