In the light of this opinion, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can function properly and keep up with the latest technologies."
Brussels asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem in view of the proliferation of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
"The researchers confirm that we have cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with the Member States and stakeholders, is ready to examine possible measures to protect children and adolescents exposed to noise from portable players and similar devices," said a member of the committee.
The current European safety standard defines the maximum noise level that portable music players can emit in 100 dB, but there is growing concern about the hearing loss caused by the excessive use of such sources.
At the same time, there are solutions such as reducing the level and duration of noise exposure, which can significantly reduce the hearing loss.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee explains that for users of portable players who listen to music for five hours a week at a high volume (more than 89 decibels), noise exposure exceeds the current maximum value for noise at work.
If a person listens to music for a longer period of time under similar conditions, after five years there is a risk of permanent hearing loss.
This affects about 5-10 percent of users of the portable device, which can reach 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
