The Elite in Danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion bailout bill presented by the White House: the majority of Americans were more interested in and still interested in the punishment of Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by the New York Times yesterday, which reports that the current crisis has led to a break-up within the Republican Party, which shows an increasing division between the traditional, restrained, supportive Eastern Coastal approach to federal institutions and business circles and the ever-growing new anti-Washington and financial world trend in the central and southern states.
This approach was expressed in a critical way in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, this event is just one of the major changes that the economic transformation that is still taking place is forecasting or allowing to be seen, not only in the United States, but throughout the Western world and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and Europe, will only speed up the phenomena that have been in place for a long time, which will be consolidated in this new atmosphere and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-activation, the re-establishment of a dual category of state sovereignty in the public consciousness of a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects banking and financial institutions which, while maintaining close links with foreign countries, are primarily and fairly widespread, bringing with them people and families who live in a single country, a single state.
This, in turn, is a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those who are also electors.
So the economic crisis seems global, but in political terms it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to have essentially been lashed outside the coastline: the eloquent proof of this is the European Union, which is unable to define a single political line between different interests and different national strategies.
Thus, everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the opening of new rules, but most of all the funds: because in a difficult situation, only individual states have economic resources, a financial stock that can make things right.
They also have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that will probably never be possessed by any other market or international organisation to that extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the nation-state is fully in line with the fact that recent economic growth attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, the increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we just had to realize that our future increasingly depends on things that are not abstract like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, but are wholly connected to a demarcated place, to an area.
So whoever controls the area has much more percussion cards than he who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
This would also translate to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fracture line.
Whoever says territory, state, government, necessarily also says: politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis appears to have produced two contiguous phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, for those who can take control of events.
On the other hand, current leadership, in particular economic leaders, is leading to a total loss of credit, who have proved to be completely inadequate and have proven that much is yet to be obscured.
Together, the two are even more profound and, in a sense, more disturbing: a feeling of credit loss, impatience, incompetence and separation that affects the entire elite of leaders in an increasing number of Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that the belief that the time of the social elite, which has reached its peak, has come to an end in an ever-increasing number of people seems to be growing. It has passed before they had their actions, their experiences, their lifestyles, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, taken over by the social elite, which is becoming increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In short, the need for leadership, in a veiled form, is fueling a diverse but strong delegation movement against the ruling class and against the traditional political system of the United States. This is reflected in the unanticipated “disruptions” of voters or, in recent times, in sudden changes in public moods. For example, the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties and programs, and even with its habits, its press and its renowned intellect, is becoming less and less able to represent what has been going on for some time in the deeper strata of Western society.
To be honest, it would be an exaggeration to talk about "the impending rebellion of the masses."
But it doesn't hurt to walk with your eyes open.
