Students suffering from expensive rental fees can cost up to 900 euros in a room
The market for student accommodation is not affected by the crisis.
According to a recent survey by Sunia, the Tenants’ Union, a student can pay up to 900 euros for a single room in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"Today, the phenomenon has reached such incredible proportions that, because of the enormous total cost to families, it has shut down a wide range of students from the opportunity to learn," explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia study office. "In these cities, the high demand from students has distorted the market to such an extent that a general process of growth has begun with local residents."
In most cases, real estate offers also contain a number of irregularities: unregistered contracts with no restrictions on rent, linked to a lease.
According to Sunia, an extraordinary measure would be needed to enable prices to be maximised through the revision of the tax system.
Details of the survey show that in Milan, around Brianza, 450 euros are requested for a bed; the price of a single room ranges from 650 euros (Bande Nere area) to an average of 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera), but it can reach 900 euros (Vittoria area).
In Florence, one bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where most students live near the university, a bed costs 250/280 euros when it comes to double rooms and 370-500 euros when it comes to single rooms.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are requested for a single bed and 450 for a double bed.
Somewhat cheaper (550 euros for a single room) prices around other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You can save some in the suburban districts: it costs 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar districts.
In Naples, 300/450 euros are requested for a bed, from 400 to 600 euros for a room. The price is highest in the area of Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, you will have to pay 250/350 euros for a single bed and at least 350 euros for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they represent a greater weight within the urban budget.
In cities such as Perugia, where students outside the EU are often looking for accommodation, there is another disorder: the rent requested from foreign students is about 25-30 percent higher than for Italian tenants.
Good-bye old Cinema Paradiso, the time of the old cinema rooms in the cities has come to a close
Traditional cinemas are closed for the benefit of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas, a blind city, is like a face without eyes.”
The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore show effectively what is happening in the Italian cities, but also in the rural regions.
Expropriation of cinemas - the appearance of large multi-room cinemas in the suburbs and, as a result, the disappearance of single-room cinemas in the city centres - is an inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it's like a friend goes away, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says Cinema Paradiso director. The film, which was an Oscar award twenty years ago and a grand prize for the Cannes festival, tells the story of the lyrics of a small-town cinema that may have been lost after a movie.
The data provided by the largest association of operators, Anec, is clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed. The biggest loss was recorded by cinemas in major cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is among the most affected regions, which lost 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the proliferation of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance is no more than the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions of Italy: in the last five years, the number of rooms has increased by 195 in Lombardy, 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia-Romagna.
“The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally,” says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. “It’s okay to build new facilities, but the survival of those that already exist should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not every one of them is willing to go into multiplexes.
Not to mention unfilled financial funds intended to support operators: the government’s overdue debt can be set at around EUR 10 million.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
To maintain the market, it would take EUR 16-18 million a year."
This is the first Italian city to decide, in its concerns over closures, to remedy the problem by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost the single-room cinemas outside and downtown.
The provisions would include tax advantages for operators and benefits for the public in order to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive into restricted areas and park in certain parking lots at a reduced rate.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even by introducing other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
But it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the domination of multiplex, need to improve the sound and image quality, because today’s audience is much more demanding.
Protecting the traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: closing the Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that made me finally do Cinema Paradiso, even though I've been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to Via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or Quirinale so as not to see the posters blacked out of the dust, I turn my head around.
