The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones come
An inexhaustible source of energy, which accounts for 70 percent of the planet’s surface, and which is still being discovered by large international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tides, and renewable energy sources that giants like Chevron have been eyeing, trying to put their hands on.
For hundreds of years, they have been looking for ways to generate energy from the movements of the sea. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of using marine energy was set aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the rise in oil prices are giving the industry a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) estimates in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore installations.
This is twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 on a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolution when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are voting for marine energy, including those who have been committed supporters of traditional energy so far.
“Chevron is studying technologies that utilize ocean energy and is considering working with us,” a spokesman for the US oil giant’s affiliate company, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of the necessary permission to launch the Alaskan project for the exploitation of marine energy, issued by the U.S. Energy Commission.
This is of little importance, especially considering that the US is currently engaged in oil extraction in Alaska, and even President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are on the way to extract energy from the sea. The amount invested so far, as you can know about the details, is evidence of growing interest.
Technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, this is still a primitive technology, just because the energy from the sea does not dispel the doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size and therefore do not cause too much problems with the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce more energy on a larger scale, installations with a more significant environmental impact are needed.
There are several options: for example, Ocean Power uses a connected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down turn the pistons and cylinders in them into hydraulic pressure.
The pressure turns on a turbine that feeds a generator.
Electricity flows to the mainland on cables under the sea.
At the same time, there are four similar types of facilities in the planning phase, which are only waiting for a federal license, and some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started power generation for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six submersible turbines located in the East River Sealine in New York City.
At a tide, the movement of water rotates the blades of the turbines, and this movement of rotation feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permits to use energy.
It's a tide after the waves.
At present, special attention is needed to exploit the opportunities that can be exploited through the tide.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tidal is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, so it can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008, just to exploit the energy provided by the tide, which is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
